5. Functional Requirements

5.1 User Management

* Users must be able to register and log in securely.
* Authentication sessions must be maintained securely.
* Dashboard must display total agents, recent matches, and leaderboard rank.

5.2 Agent Configuration
Users must provide:

* Agent Name
* Selected Game
* Algorithm selection (Q-Learning, SARSA, DQN, PPO, A2C)
* Learning Rate
* Number of Episodes
* Exploration Rate (Epsilon where applicable)

System must validate hyperparameters before training begins.

5.3 Training Engine

* System runs episodes in backend using PyTorch models.
* Game state data is processed per step.
* Reward calculation per episode.
* Live reward graph streamed via WebSockets.
* Model auto-saved in .pt format after training completion.
* Agent added to Agent Library.

5.4 Game Environments

* Snake
* Connect 4
* Flappy Bird
* Maze
* Pong

Each environment must expose:

* State representation
* Action space
* Reward function
* Episode termination conditions

5.5 Arena Module

* Users select two agents and a game.
* Real-time match visualization.
* Step-by-step state updates via WebSockets.
* Match result persistence.
* Leaderboard auto-update.

5.6 Explainability Panel
During matches, system must display:

* Q-values or policy probabilities
* Confidence score
* Exploration rate (if applicable)

5.7 Statistics Module

* Win rate
* Average score
* Best score
* Training performance metrics

5.8 Report Generation
System must generate downloadable PDF report containing:

* Training reward graphs
* Hyperparameters used
* Performance summary
* Final statistics

6. Non-Functional Requirements

* System must support concurrent user sessions.
* Real-time updates must have latency below 500ms.
* Model training must not block frontend operations.
* Backend must handle multi-threaded or asynchronous training.
* System must maintain model persistence integrity.
* Secure authentication and encrypted credential storage.

7. System Architecture Overview

Frontend Layer:
HTML, CSS, JavaScript UI components including dashboard, training interface, arena view, stats page.

Backend Layer:
Flask REST APIs for user management and configuration.
Flask-SocketIO for real-time streaming (training graphs and matches).

AI Layer:
PyTorch-based reinforcement learning implementations.
Algorithm abstraction layer supporting multiple RL techniques.

Database Layer:
Relational database storing users, agents, match results, leaderboard, and statistics.

Storage Layer:
Local file system for model (.pt) storage.

8. Data Sources and Datasets

The system does not rely on static datasets. Training data is generated dynamically through reinforcement learning via environment interaction and self-play.

Game state data includes:

* Board states
* Agent positions
* Object positions
* Score states

All state transitions are stored temporarily during training and summarized post-training.

9. AI/ML Models and Algorithms

Q-Learning:
Tabular method used for small state-space environments such as Maze.

SARSA:
On-policy learning for stable grid-based environments.

DQN (Deep Q-Network):
Neural network approximation for high-dimensional state spaces such as Snake and Connect 4.

PPO (Proximal Policy Optimization):
Policy-gradient algorithm optimized for timing-based games like Flappy Bird and Pong.

A2C (Advantage Actor-Critic):
Baseline actor-critic method for stable training across supported games.

All models are implemented using PyTorch and saved in .pt format.

